every pair is merged, only then do we explore all outgoing transitions but then we could have a few outgoing transitions with the same label from the same group of states

front line=equivalence classes rather than just states - I could do this via List<String,CmpVertex> - for normal states, this is a Map, for equivalence classes, this is a List to permit multiple outgoing transitions with the same label

Green digits: the order in which equivalence classes are formed. Red digigs: the order in which transitions are explored if I do a depth-first traversal. Purpose: to justify how I could end up with an equivalence class containing many outgoing transitions with the same label. Note that if I do depth-first traversal, A,B1 is pushed onto stack before transition c is taken, hence we end up with multiple occurences of red node pairs on the stack - not an issue because once we merged one, all other ones are automatically discarded by the check that we should only explore an equivalence class which we just formed from a pair on a stack.
Non-PTA merging can cause two _groups_ of states which were previously merged, to get merged together

Justification: when a pair of transition is matched, a two-state equiv class is created. If there are more matching pairs (in case of circular diagrams), more states from PTA are added to equivalence classes, one per extra transition. This justifies the formula above. This implies that we could do the same in the most general case where we are talking of merging of stats in an arbitrary graph. Not sure though how much sense it would make there.

This is not such an unreasonable measure: the more states get merged together, the impact the merge of a pair of state is. One can argue that this means that more "related" parts of the graph are merged together.

The last sum adds together transitions between states in each equivalence class. This is not entirely true because some of those get collapsed because of a loop around one of those states. At the same time, an arbitrary pair can be collapsed beause paths leading to elements of the pair are collapsed but not to do with transitions between those two states. I might have to distinguish between these cases. A possible way to calculate this is to consider whether if we have a pair of states from eq class A from which we could reach a pair where one of those states is already in A.
